article.description: Orlando broke a four-game losing streak Friday night, beating the Utah Starzz 84-73 as Shannon Johnson had 21 points and matched a career-high with 12 assists.
article.headline: With new attitude, Miracle get new result
article.linkText: Orlando beats Utah to end four-game slide
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Orlando Miracle have their attitude back and now they hope wins will follow. Orlando broke a four-game losing streak Friday night, beating the Utah Starzz 84-73 as Shannon Johnson had 21 points and matched a career-high with 12 assists. "We started out very strong and very confident, then we lost our swagger,'' said Johnson, who had Orlando's first double-double of the season. "That's when you go out and play hard, but don't see the end result of a win. You start looking for answers of how to win. You start doing that and you end up losing.'' Nykesha Sales, Clarisse Machanguana and Wendy Palmer all added 14 points for Orlando (10-10). Adrienne Johnson came off the bench to score 11. The Miracle, using an offense that mostly stayed outside, matched their season high with 10 3-pointers in 16 attempts. Orlando coach Dee Brown made it a priority to keep the ball on the perimeter -- and away from Utah's 7-foot-2 center Margo Dydek. She blocked 19 shots in Utah's last four games -- all wins -- but had only two against Orlando. "Her comfort zone is in the paint,'' Brown said. "We ran every play we had to make her run out of the paint and guard either (Johnson or Sales), but she didn't come out. So, our guards had free reign.'' Orlando shot 51.7 percent (31-for-60) but was outscored in the paint 40-12. Johnson single-handedly put the game away early in the second half, scoring 12 points, eight on free throws, in a span of less than five minutes. Her two foul shots with 10:46 left put the Miracle ahead 62-50, and the Starzz couldn't get the deficit under 12 points until less than 30 seconds remained. "(Johnson) controlled the game the way a point guard should,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. The Miracle led by as many as 21 points until Utah rallied against Orlando's substitutes in the final four minutes. Dydek had 18 points and eight rebounds for the Starzz (14-7), while Andrea Gardner had 14 points and Marie Ferdinand and Natalie Williams added 12 each. Orlando made its first five shots, including two 3-pointers, to open a 12-4 lead barely three minutes into the game. That was the biggest deficit Utah had experienced in five games. Although the Starzz quickly rallied to tie, Orlando kept the pressure on behind hot outside shooting. The Miracle made a season-high six 3-pointers in the first half -- with Sales and Palmer each perfect on three attempts -- and led 44-38 at halftime. "Our game plan was to not allow the 3-point shot,'' Harvey said. "We tried every way to stop them. The bottom line is, if we give up 2s and not 3s, it's a closer game.''

Notes: The Starzz's winning streak was their longest since an eight-game run from last July 24-Aug. 7. ... Orlando was without reserve center Jessie Hicks, serving a one-game suspension for punching Charlotte's Summer Erb in a loss Wednesday night. ... Harvey was hit with a technical foul with 11:04 remaining in the first half. She was complaining that Dydek didn't get a foul call when double-teamed in the low post. ... NBA players Tracy McGrady and Chucky Atkins were among the 8,427 in attendance.
